&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;How to Engage for Imparting Knowledge 
    &lt;div id=&#34;how-to-engage-for-imparting-knowledge&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    
    &lt;span
        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100&#34;&gt;
        &lt;a class=&#34;group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700&#34;
            style=&#34;text-decoration-line: none !important;&#34; href=&#34;#how-to-engage-for-imparting-knowledge&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;        
    
&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The biggest counterproductive assumption a teacher  &lt;br&gt;
or a trainer can make about the class is  &lt;br&gt;
&amp;ldquo;they all know what they want to learn and why they want to learn&amp;rdquo;.  &lt;br&gt;
If so, then the problem is already known.  &lt;br&gt;
Hence, let’s start with a solution and give gyan to these people.  &lt;br&gt;
But this assumption is wrong.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
